Methinks I&#39;m not satisfied with the Ing solution. Spelling it that way, 
Bon becomes &quot;bong&quot; boN and if you can&#39;t let others know that your/ bon 
/temps doesn&#39;t mean &quot;bong&quot; times, you might end up in jail! :-)

There&#39;s simply no QS letter for that nazalization. I would probably use 
an apostrophe + Ing: *Bo&#39;ng. *I feel the apostrophe gives a warning, 
like it&#39;s common use for glottal stops that the following sound isn&#39;t 
really pronounced, and the Ing gives a great hint of the flavor it gives 
the preceding vowel. Of course, I know that it&#39;s not a purist solution, 
but we&#39;re talking about extending it beyond what it was designed for. 
Until more letters are created (!) I vote for &#39;N (apostrophe + Ing) to 
indicate French and Portuguese nazalized vowels.

&gt;&gt;Also, I don&#39;t find anything either in Quikscript or in Shavian for the
&gt;&gt;pure nasal as in &quot;bon jour&quot;. In &quot;bon&quot; the o is nasalized, thus the n
&gt;&gt;is not a consonant. The Shavian n stands for the consonant n as in
&gt;&gt;bonfire.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;The fact is that we do use Fremch words in English. &quot;Elan&quot; comes to
&gt;&gt;mind as an example, but there should obviously be other examples too.
&gt;&gt;How would one write &quot;elan&quot; in Shavian?
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;I would put an Ing after the vowel.  There is nothing in French it can 
&gt;be confused with.
&gt;  
&gt;

